explanation:
Each listed symbol is referenced (directly or indirectly) by OS_TimerDelete and must be inspected to determine whether any for loops that affect MISRA Rule (well‑formed for loops) exist or whether objects used as loop counters/control are modified in called code:

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl: called at function start; its implementation may contain for loops or side effects relevant to rule checking.
- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: argument to OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl; inspect for side effects or internal for loops.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: central lookup used twice; its implementation (and its transitive callees) may contain for loops or modify objects that could be used as loop counters.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: used by lock/unlock implementations (transitive callee) — may contain loops; needed for full analysis of called code inside OS_TimerDelete.
- OS_ObjectIdTransferToken: transfers token state; needed to understand whether token/state used in any loop conditions could be altered by this call.
- OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl: called while manipulating callback ring; its body and transitive callees may contain for loops or modify shared objects used in loops.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: used repeatedly to compute IDs from tokens; its semantics needed to determine whether it modifies or relies on objects that could be loop counters.
- OS_ObjectIdEqual: used in callback list comparisons; its implementation must be seen to ensure it has no persistent side effects and does not alter loop control objects.
- OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl: counterpart to lock; inspect for internal loops or side effects that could affect loop analysis.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: completes deletion and calls other routines; its implementation (and transitive callees) must be inspected for for loops or side effects that relate to loop counters.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: called to release the timebase token; may call routines with for loops (transaction finish) so must be checked.
- OS_ObjectIdDefined: used to decide whether to delete the dedicated timebase; check implementation for side effects or loops.
- OS_TimeBaseDelete: called conditionally at end; its body may contain for loops and must be validated (it is also in the call graph as a caller/callee of similar routines).
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro (or accessor) used to read object table entries (timecb/timebase); inspect expansion to ensure it does not introduce loops or modify loop-control objects.
- OS_timecb_table / OS_timebase_table: data objects accessed via OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; structure/layout and accessors must be known to see whether table access relies on or modifies loop counters.
- OS_timecb_internal_record_t / OS_timebase_internal_record_t: data types of table entries (members next_cb, prev_cb, first_cb are modified) — necessary to check whether these modifications could violate the rule when used inside any for loops.
- OS_object_token_t: token type manipulated and passed to other routines; its semantics may affect loop conditions in called code.
- TIMECB_FLAG_DEDICATED_TIMEBASE: flag tested in an if; its definition is required to check whether it is or could be used as a loop control flag elsewhere.
- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: constant used for initialization; needed to determine whether uses/assignments to it could be mistaken for loop-counter modifications.

Note: to fully determine compliance with the MISRA for‑loop rule you must examine the implementations (and transitive callees) of the above functions/macros and the definitions of the listed types/constants because the rule applies to any for loop body and includes behaviour of any functions called within that statement. The list above covers the direct callees and the data/macros that OS_TimerDelete manipulates and that are most likely to participate in or affect for‑loop control.
